ultiple times to find competent suppliers' (Avoma note). (4) Slow contract access\u2014'locating specific contracts across business units can take a day or two' (Avoma). (5) Tail spend poorly managed\u2014no robust automated tool. (6) Manual/inconsistent sourcing processes limiting automation. (7) Governance adaptability\u2014current tools too rigid for dynamic process changes; 'need a flexible, configurable system that adapts to changing governance without lengthy vendor dependency' (Avoma). Pain owner: Jamila (operational) and Sameh (strategic). Pain is confirmed and specific; quantification is the gap."}, "paper_process": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["MEDDPICC 2.0 CRM entry 8 Jun 2026"], "narrative": "Contracting mechanics not yet discussed (no MSA, SOW, legal review, or InfoSec mentioned on calls). Government holding company likely requires legal review by government counsel and Board-level approval depending on contract value. MEDDPICC 2.0 flags 'whether the procurement process requires public tender, lowest-bid preference, or government authority sign-off' as unknown. Integration scoping for SAP S/4HANA and Oman government e-tendering platform will be part of SOW but feasibility not yet validated. No SI/partner role mentioned. Paper process clarity is a gap; need to surface approval chain, legal review requirements, and whether public tender rules apply during the business-case / pre-RFP phase."}, "economic_buyer": {"status": "confirmed", "sources": ["MEDDPICC 2.0 CRM entry 8 Jun 2026", "Avoma touchpoint manifest 11 Jun 2026 (Sameh attended demo)"], "narrative": "Sameh Bartok, SVP Contracts & Procurement, is the economic buyer. MEDDPICC 2.0 states 'He attended the call, confirmed strategic direction, and holds executive authority. Any system procurement requires his sanction.' He attended the 11 Jun demo (touchpoint manifest). Budget is currently assigned to the SAP S/4HANA ERP rollout; S2P is under review within that envelope. Sameh is the likely budget 